<EFX_CONTROL_AND_PROCEDURES>
<A NAME="FIS_CONTROL_AND_PROCEDURES"></A>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="9%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
<A NAME="D128680D10K_HTM_TX128680_16">
</A>
	Item&nbsp;9A.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Controls and Procedures.
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(a)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Evaluation of Disclosure Controls and Procedures.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company carried out an evaluation as of the end of the
	period covered by this report, under the supervision and with the participation of the Company&#146;s management, including the Company&#146;s Chief Executive Officer and Chief Financial Officer, of the effectiveness of the design and operation of
	the Company&#146;s disclosure controls and procedures pursuant to Rules&nbsp;13a-15 and 15d-15 of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended (the &#147;Exchange Act&#148;). Based upon that evaluation, the Chief Executive Officer and Chief
	Financial Officer concluded that the Company&#146;s disclosure controls and procedures are effective in ensuring that all information required in the reports it files or submits under the Exchange Act was accumulated and communicated to the
	Company&#146;s management, including its Chief Executive Officer and Chief Financial Officer, as appropriate to allow timely decisions regarding required disclosure and was recorded, processed, summarized and reported within the time period required
	by the rules and regulations of the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:18PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(b)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Changes in Internal Control over Financial Reporting.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	There have been no changes in internal control over
	financial reporting that occurred during the last fiscal quarter that have materially affected, or are reasonably likely to materially affect, the Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:18PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(c)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Management&#146;s Annual Report on Internal Control over Financial Reporting.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The management of Domino&#146;s
	Pizza, Inc. is responsible for establishing and maintaining adequate internal control over financial reporting. Internal control over financial reporting is defined in Rule&nbsp;13a-15(f) promulgated under the Exchange Act, as a process designed by,
	or under the supervision of, the Company&#146;s principal executive and principal financial officers and effected by the Company&#146;s board of directors, management and other personnel, to provide reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of
	financial reporting and the preparation of financial statements for external purposes in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles. Because of its inherent limitations, internal control over financial reporting may not prevent or
	detect misstatements. Also, projections of any evaluation of effectiveness to future periods are subject to the risk that controls may become inadequate because of changes in conditions, or that the degree of compliance with the policies or
	procedures may deteriorate. Under the supervision and with the participation of the Company&#146;s management, including its Chief Executive Officer and Chief Financial Officer, the Company conducted an evaluation of the effectiveness of its
	internal control over financial reporting as of January&nbsp;3, 2016 based on the framework in
<I>
	Internal Control&nbsp;&#151; Integrated Framework (2013)&nbsp;
</I>
	issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission. Based
	on that evaluation, management concluded that its internal control over financial reporting was effective as of January&nbsp;3, 2016. The effectiveness of the Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting as of January&nbsp;3, 2016, has
	been audited by PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP, an independent registered public accounting firm, as stated in their report which appears herein.
</P>
</EFX_CONTROL_AND_PROCEDURES>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:18PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<EFX_OTHER_INFORMATION>
<A NAME="FIS_OTHER_INFORMATION"></A>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="9%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
<A NAME="D128680D10K_HTM_TX128680_17">
</A>
	Item&nbsp;9B.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Other Information.
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As previously reported on a Current Report on Form 8-K filed with the Securities and
	Exchange Commission (the &#147;SEC&#148;), on April&nbsp;22, 2015, our stockholders approved a proposal to amend our Second Restated Certificate of Incorporation to declassify our Board of Directors. The related Certificate of Amendment to our
	Second Restated Certificate of Incorporation, dated June&nbsp;16, 2015, was filed as Exhibit 3.2 to our Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q for the period ended June&nbsp;14, 2015, as filed with the SEC on July&nbsp;16, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On February&nbsp;24, 2016, our Board of Directors approved, effective immediately, the Second Amended and Restated By-Laws (the &#147;By-Laws&#148;) to
	implement conforming changes to the By-Laws in light of the declassification of the Board, including the deletion of Sections 3.3 and 3.5 and revisions to Section&nbsp;3.13 (previously Section&nbsp;3.15) to allow for the removal of directors with or
	without cause.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The foregoing description of the By-Laws, as amended and restated, is qualified in its entirety by reference to the full text of the
	By-Laws, a copy of which is filed as Exhibit 3.3 hereto and incorporated herein by reference.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	72
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	David A. Brandon
</I>
</B>
	has served as our Chairman of the Board of Directors since March 1999. Mr.&nbsp;Brandon is
	currently Chairman and CEO of Toys &#147;R&#148; Us, Inc., the world&#146;s largest specialty retailer of toy and baby products. Previously, he was the Director of Athletics at the University of Michigan from March 2010 to October 2014.
	Mr.&nbsp;Brandon has served as our Chairman of the Board of Directors since March 1999 and also served as Chief Executive Officer from March 1999 to March 2010. Mr.&nbsp;Brandon was retained by the Company as a Special Advisor from March 2010 to
	January 2011. Prior to joining Domino&#146;s, Mr.&nbsp;Brandon was President and Chief Executive Officer of Valassis, Inc., a company in the sales promotion and coupon industries, from 1989 to 1998 and Chairman of the Board of Directors of Valassis,
	Inc. from 1997 to 1998. In addition to serving on the Boards of Directors for Domino&#146;s and Toys &#147;R&#148; Us, Mr.&nbsp;Brandon also serves on the boards of DTE Energy and Herman Miller Inc. He previously served on the boards of Burger King
	Corporation, Kaydon Corporation, Northwest Airlines and the TJX Companies, Inc.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	J. Patrick Doyle
</I>
</B>
	has served as our President and Chief
	Executive Officer since March 2010 and was appointed to the Board of Directors in February 2010. Mr.&nbsp;Doyle served as President, Domino&#146;s USA from September 2007 to March 2010, Executive Vice President, Team USA from 2004 to 2007, Executive
	Vice President of International from May 1999 to October 2004 and as interim Executive Vice President of Build the Brand from December 2000 to July 2001. Mr.&nbsp;Doyle served as Senior Vice President of Marketing from the time he joined
	Domino&#146;s in 1997 until May 1999. Mr.&nbsp;Doyle serves on the Board of Directors of Best Buy Co., Inc. and also previously served on the Boards of Directors of G&amp;K Services, Inc.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Jeffrey D. Lawrence
</I>
</B>
	has served as Chief Financial Officer and Executive Vice President since August 2015. He previously served as Vice President
	&#150; Finance and Treasurer from January 2014 to August 2015, and as Vice President of International Finance, Strategy&nbsp;&amp; Insights and Administration from 2008 to January 2014. Prior to joining the International team, Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence
	served as Vice President and Corporate Controller from 2002 to 2008. Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence began his career at Domino&#146;s in 2000. Prior to joining Domino&#146;s, Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence was a Manager of Audit and Business Advisory Services in the Detroit
	office of Arthur Andersen LLP.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Eric B. Anderson
</I>
</B>
	has served as Executive Vice President of International Operations since January 2016.
	Mr.&nbsp;Anderson joined Domino&#146;s in 2010 as regional vice president for the&nbsp;Americas&nbsp;and business strategy. In 2012, he took over as regional vice president of Domino&#146;s EMEA (Europe,&nbsp;Middle East,&nbsp;and Africa) region.
	Prior to joining Domino&#146;s, Anderson was a leader in the restaurant and retail practice of Bain&nbsp;&amp; Company, a global strategic consulting firm, where he was also a founding member of Bain&#146;s Corporate Renewal Group, a specialized
	turnaround management group that led hands-on turnarounds of distressed companies.
</P>

</B>
	has served as our Executive Vice President,
	Supply Chain Services since June 2015. Prior to joining Domino&#146;s, Mr.&nbsp;Ellis served as senior vice president of conversion of Coca-Cola Refreshments, overseeing manufacturing, transportation planning and third-party logistics. Prior to that
	role, he spent nearly three years as senior vice president of manufacturing after joining Coca-Cola Refreshments in 2010. From 2000 to 2010, Mr.&nbsp;Ellis held various leadership roles with Coca-Cola Enterprises including central business unit vice
	president of supply chain. Prior to joining Coca-Cola, he worked for Kimberly Clark Corp. and PepsiCo, after serving in the U.S. Army from 1988-1991.

	programs at the&nbsp;University of Minnesota. Ms.&nbsp;Werthauser was also the co-owner and operations leader of Aljohn&#146;s and Junkyard Retailers, a diverse retailing and manufacturing company that she grew from one to 11 locations.

<B>
<I>
	C. Andrew Ballard
</I>
</B>
	has served on our Board of Directors since July 2015 and is a member of the
	Compensation Committee. Mr.&nbsp;Ballard currently serves as the CEO and Co-founder of Quad Analytix, a technology and data company, and is also the Founder and Managing Partner of Figtree Partners, an investment firm focused on digital media. In
	addition, he serves as the Vice Chairman of Zignal Labs, and is a Senior Advisor at the private equity firm Hellman&nbsp;&amp; Friedman, where he was previously a Managing Director. Prior to joining Hellman&nbsp;&amp; Friedman in 2003,
	Mr.&nbsp;Ballard worked at Bain Capital in San Francisco and Boston, as well as Bain&nbsp;&amp; Company from 1994 to 2002. In addition to serving on Domino&#146;s Board, Mr.&nbsp;Ballard is the chair of the board of trustees and chair of the
	investment committee of the San Francisco Foundation. He is also currently a board member of I Have a Dream San Francisco, and is actively involved with Family Connections, a tuition free preschool for under-served families. Mr.&nbsp;Ballard has
	held previous board roles at Activant Solutions, Catalina Marketing, DoubleClick, Getty Images, Internet Brands and Vertafore.

</I>

	has served on our Board of Directors since March 1999, serves as the Chairperson of the Compensation Committee of the Board of Directors and also serves on the Nominating and Corporate Governance Committee of the Board of Directors.
	Mr.&nbsp;Balson is currently the CEO of Match Beyond. Prior to becoming the CEO of Match Beyond, Mr.&nbsp;Balson was a Managing Director at Bain Capital, a global investment company, from 2001 to 2013. Mr.&nbsp;Balson became a Principal of Bain
	Capital in June 1998. Mr.&nbsp;Balson serves on the Boards of Directors of Bloomin&#146; Brands, Inc. Mr.&nbsp;Balson also previously served on the Boards of Directors of FleetCor Technologies, Inc., Dunkin&#146; Brands, Inc., Skylark Co., Ltd., and
	numerous private companies.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

<I>
	Diana F. Cantor
</I>
</B>
	has served on our Board of Directors since October 2005, serves as the Chairperson of the Audit
	Committee of the Board of Directors and also serves on the Nominating and Corporate Governance Committee of the Board of Directors. Ms.&nbsp;Cantor joined Alternative Investment Management, LLC as a Partner in January 2010 and is the Vice Chairman
	of the Virginia Retirement System, where she also serves on the Audit and Compliance Committee. Ms.&nbsp;Cantor was a Managing Director with New York Private Bank and Trust from January 2008 through the end of 2009. Ms.&nbsp;Cantor served as
	Executive Director of the Virginia College Savings Plan, the state&#146;s 529 college savings program, from 1996 to January 2008. Ms.&nbsp;Cantor served seven years as Vice President of Richmond Resources, Ltd. from 1990 through 1996, and as Vice
	President of Goldman, Sachs&nbsp;&amp; Co. from 1985 to 1990. Ms.&nbsp;Cantor is also a member of the Board of Directors of Media General, Inc. and Universal Corporation, and she previously served on the Boards of Directors of Revlon, Inc., Vistage
	International, Knowledge Universe &#150; US, Edelman Financial Services and Service King Body and Paint LLC.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

	Richard L. Federico
</I>
</B>
	has served
	on our Board of Directors since February 2011 and also serves on the Compensation Committee of the Board of Directors. Mr.&nbsp;Federico is currently the Executive Chairman of P.F. Chang&#146;s China Bistro Inc., based in Scottsdale, Arizona.
	Mr.&nbsp;Federico previously served as the Chairman and Chief Executive Officer or Co-Chief Executive Officer of P.F. Chang&#146;s from September 1997 to March 2015. Mr.&nbsp;Federico serves as the Chairman of the Board of Directors of Jamba Inc.,
	and is a founding director of Chances for Children.
<B>
<I>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	James A. Goldman
</I>
</B>
	has served on our Board of Directors since March 2010
	and also serves on the Compensation Committee of the Board of Directors. Mr.&nbsp;Goldman served as President and CEO and Board member of Godiva Chocolatier Inc., based in New York City from 2004 to 2014. He was President of the Food and Beverage
	Division at Campbell Soup Company from 2001 to 2004. He worked in various executive positions at Nabisco Inc. from 1992 to 2000. Prior to his work at Nabisco Inc., Mr.&nbsp;Goldman was a senior consulting associate at McKinsey&nbsp;&amp; Co.
	Mr.&nbsp;Goldman served as a member of the Board of Directors at The Children&#146;s Place Retail from 2006 to 2008, on the Compensation Committee. Mr.&nbsp;Goldman is currently on the Board of Trustees of Save the Children in Fairfield, CT, the
	Board of Directors of the International Tennis Hall of Fame in Newport, Rhode Island and the Advisory Board of Feed Projects in New York, NY. He also served on the Board of Trustees at the YMCA Camps Becket and Chimney Corners in Becket,
	Massachusetts, from 1992 to 1998.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Vernon &#147;Bud&#148; O. Hamilton
</I>
</B>
	has served on our Board of Directors since May 2005, serves as the
	Chairperson of the Nominating and Corporate Governance Committee of the Board of Directors and also serves on the Audit Committee. Mr.&nbsp;Hamilton served in various executive positions for Procter&nbsp;&amp; Gamble from 1966 through 2003.
	Mr.&nbsp;Hamilton most recently served as Vice President, Innovation-Research&nbsp;&amp; Development-Global from 2002 through 2003 and served as Vice President of Procter&nbsp;&amp; Gamble Customer Business Development-North America from 1999 to
	2001, Vice President of Procter&nbsp;&amp; Gamble Customer Marketing-North America from 1996 through 1998 and President of Eurocos, a wholly-owned subsidiary of Procter&nbsp;&amp; Gamble, from 1994 to 1995.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	75
</P>

	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Gregory A. Trojan
</I>
</B>
	has served on our Board of Directors since March 2010 and also serves on the
	Audit Committee of the Board of Directors. Mr.&nbsp;Trojan is currently the CEO and President of BJ&#146;s Restaurants, Inc., a casual dining restaurant company located in Huntington Beach, California. He was elected to the BJ&#146;s Board of
	Directors in December 2012. Prior to joining BJ&#146;s, he was the CEO of Guitar Center, Inc. from 2010 through 2012, where he served as President and Chief Operating Officer from 2007 to 2010. From 1998 to 2006, he was CEO of House of Blues
	Entertainment, Inc., having served as the Company&#146;s President from 1996 to 1998. Mr.&nbsp;Trojan worked in various executive positions at PepsiCo Inc. from 1990 to 1996, most recently as CEO of California Pizza Kitchen. Prior to that, he was a
	consultant at Bain&nbsp;&amp; Company, The Wharton Small Business Development Center and Arthur Andersen&nbsp;&amp; Co. In addition, he previously served on the Board of Directors of Oakley, Inc.
</P>

	filed within 120 days of January&nbsp;3, 2016.

<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="3%">

	DOMINO&#146;S PIZZA, INC.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<U>
	NOTES TO PARENT COMPANY FINANCIAL STATEMENTS
</U>

<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(1)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	INTRODUCTION AND BASIS OF PRESENTATION
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:10%; TEXT-INDENT:-2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Domino&#146;s Pizza, Inc., on a stand-alone basis, (the Parent Company) has accounted for majority-owned
	subsidiaries using the equity method of accounting. The accompanying condensed financial statements of the Parent Company should be read in conjunction with the consolidated financial statements of Domino&#146;s Pizza, Inc. and its subsidiaries (the
	Company) and the notes thereto included in Item&nbsp;8 of this Form 10-K. These financial statements have been provided to comply with Rule 4-08(e) of Regulation S-X.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<U>
	Cash and Cash Equivalents
</U>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:15%; TEXT-INDENT:-2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Cash equivalents consist of highly liquid investments with original maturities of three months or less at the date of
	purchase. These investments are carried at cost, which approximates fair value.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<U>
	Use of Estimates
</U>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:15%; TEXT-INDENT:-2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The use of estimates is inherent in the preparation of financial statements in accordance with generally accepted accounting
	principles. Actual results could differ from those estimates.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:18PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(2)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	SUPPLEMENTAL DISCLOSURES OF CASH FLOW INFORMATION
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:10%; TEXT-INDENT:-2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During 2015, the Parent Company received dividends from its subsidiaries primarily consisting of amounts
	received to repurchase common stock in connection with the Company&#146;s 2015 recapitalization transaction. See Note 4 to the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements as filed in this Form 10-K for a description of the recapitalization
	transaction that occurred in 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:10%; TEXT-INDENT:-2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Non-cash activities of $34.1 million, $42.3 million and $32.3 million were recorded
	in 2015, 2014 and 2013, respectively, related to stock-based compensation plans and amounts recorded in other comprehensive income related to the Company&#146;s subsidiaries.
</P>

</TD>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:1.00EM; TEXT-INDENT:-1.00EM; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	6.8
